"title\\\":\\\"Practical Tmux — mutelight.org\\\",\\\"url\\\":\\\"https://mutelight.org/practical-tmux\\\"},{\\\"title\\\":\\\"My tmux configuration – jamesoff.net\\\",\\\"url\\\":\\\"https://jamesoff.net/2017/08/26/tmux-configuration.html\\\"},{\\\"title\\\":\\\"A Quick and Easy Guide to tmux - Ham Vocke\\\",\\\"url\\\":\\\"https://hamvocke.com/blog/a-quick-and-easy-guide-to-tmux/\\\"}]\\n\\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about tmux detached session sizing workarounds:\\n\\n## Key Findings:\\n\\n**The Core Problem:** When you create a new session, detach from it, try and resize it, then dump the buffer, the session will still have the size of the terminal that created it.\\n\\n**Manual Resize Workaround:** You can manually resize the window to the correct size using the `resize-window` command with `-x` and `-y` flags, for example: `tmux resize-window -x 122 -y 50`\\n\\n**Fake Client/Attach Workaround:** The moment you reattach to the fully-detached session, it will immediately resize, which is useful if you want to force a resize by temporarily attaching with desired dimensions.\\n\\n**ignore-size Flag:** The tmux client supports an `ignore-size` flag that makes the client not affect the size of other clients, which can be relevant for headless operations.\\n\\n**Detach-on-Attach Approach:** You can add the `-d` option to the attach-session command to make it detach elsewhere, which helps manage client sizing constraints.\\n\\nThe search results indicate this is a known limitation in tmux when working with detached sessions headlessly, particularly with control mode (`-CC`) clients. The practical workarounds involve either manually resizing windows or leveraging attach/detach cycles to trigger automatic resizing.\\n\\n\\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks.\"}]},\"uuid\":\"261bb6ae-7af5-4541-abc1-9021b339661d\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-04T15:44:21.969Z\",\"toolUseResult\":{\"query\":\